Oct 6 2009 	Excellent hotel and service	My wife and I booked 5 nights in the Grosvenor House based on Trip Advisor reviews and we were not disappointed. We were met from our early mornining flight by one of the hotel's chaffuer driven BMW 7 series. It was 34 degrees at 730am so the cold flannel and water were very welcome. The driver could clearly see we were tired from the flight so didn't attempt to chat for the 30 minute drive as so many hotel chaffuers do. He just left us to relax and take in the sights.We were well aware that we wouldn't be able to check in until 2pm despite us arriving at the hotel at 8am so I had emailed the hotel previously and asked them if they could provide us with a room where we could sort oursuelves out. The reply stated that we would be able to check in straight away as long as the room was available. Unfortunately, the room wasn't ready which meant a few hours wait. We were given use of the Spa to freshen up and change into something cooler. We opted to just sit in the lobby and wait for our room to become available. After a couple of hours the receptionist came over and said we could now go to our room and because they had kept us waiting so long we had been upgraded to a suite. Firstly, we hadn't been waiting that long and secondly we full well knew that we had arrived early! They were so apologetic. I had to keep saying that it really wasn't there fault or problem for that matter. A great way to start our holiday.The room was 1 bed apartment complete with kitchen and BUTLER! Whatever we needed we just rang the butler and it was sorted - brilliant. The only 2 negatives for the room are the view of the building site opposite and the mini bar was extortionate, even in normal mini bar terms. TIP: buy duty free at the airport to take to your hotel. On the plus side the room gave us access to the private lounge on the top floor where complimentary food and drinks are served. This was excellent. In fact on 2 occasions we didn;t even go out for dinner we just had the canapes. The atomosphere is very relaxed and the sunsets views are excellent. TIP: Arrive for about 1740 for a window seat. Bar 44 opposite is also quite good after the lounge has closed.The hotel pool is not too good. It looks nice but is North facing(!) so doesn't seem to get much sun. The sun that it does get is generally blocked by surrounding sky scrapers. Instead, we used the regular shuttle service to Le Royal Meridian which is a 5 minute drive away. This hotel has 2 excellent pools and lovely gardens. Its also on the beach (which isn't that great). You don't need cash here as you can just sign for food and drinks as you would in the Grosvenor. The pool boys regularly come round with cold flannels and little shots of frozen juice to cool you down - a nice touch.Back at the Grosvenor we went to the Spa for a massage which was excellent and as you would expect for a 5 star Spa. We also used the hotel to book a Desert Safari which we highly reccommend. Be warned the 'Dune Bashing' can and will make people feel sick! The Buddah bar next door is a sight to see. It has to be one of the best decorated bars in the world. We went for food and as we arrived late were put at the back of the restaurant on our own as no other tables were available. When we told the waitress that we were staying in the hotel she disappeared and came back a few minutes later and had miraculously found us a great table right in the middle of the main restaurant! Very nice.All in all the hotel is excellent. I imagine a lot of hotels in Dubai are similar to this but I think what sets this one apart is the staff. They are so helpful but without being over bearing. They cannot do enough for you. As soon as you want something they just seem to appear and they also remember your name. When we checked out the receptionist (a different one from when we checked in) apologised for keeping us waiting on arrival. A very good operation.	
