Oct 4 2009 	GH great business hotel just average for leisure	I've stayed in GH for 4 nights for special promotion for less than €150/night. The hotel is well located for travelling in Abu Dhabi direction (e.g. opposite to Dubai centre). So we avoided some traffic jam every day. The construction of the second tower of GH means noise 24/7. However, the isolation is good and it didn't impact my sleep. Annoying is that GH is in the middle of construction site and if you want to go anywhere (beach is 300m) you have to take taxi or hotel transport. Room is spacious, luxurious materials, clean and with all usual equipment. The Bulgari amenities in the bathroom, or tea&amp;coffee were not replenished. Could be because of our short stay or negligence, who knows?The staff is very kind, polite and helpful. There is not much they can't help you with. On the other hand when we came the didn't have our reservation. Similar situation happened to my colleague the same week. Eventually everything was solved, but they have some room to improve in administration/booking.	
Oct 2 2009 	What luxury is really about!	There is hardly anything negative you could say about Grosvenor House - from the very first moment I walked into the lobby (extremely tired from a day of travelling) I was very impressed by the friendly and helpful attitude of ALL staff! Everybody you come across greets you with a smile on their face, and as soon as you stop and look as if you need something, they immediately offer their help, and are then actually able to help you!I don't want to waste any time on pointing out that the rooms are spotless, the bars in the hotel are very nice, the pool area spotless, etc etc etc. This is something you can expect from a 5 star hotel I find. What makes the Grosvenor House stand out are the little things that make it so enjoyable. For example, when you leave your room in the morning and you come back, there is always a fresh bowl of fruit waiting for you, plus a beautiful piece of cake, and sometimes a rose. As soon as you stand in front of one of the reclining chairs at the pool, there is friendly staff putting a towel onto the chair for you, and within the next minute, you have a glass filled with ice cubes and a bottle of water, plus a cooled apple or pear. These little perks pop up everywhere, and make you feel pampered in a not-in-your-face kind of way.For the travellers who want to explore Dubai: staff are extremely competent in booking tours for you at the hotel, so you really don't have to plan ahead. Also, cab rides are very cheap, so you can get anywhere in Dubai for less than 60 dirham (around US20), and to the main attractions usually between 30-50 dirham. The adjacent bars and restaurants are absolutely beautiful, and I think you would seriously miss out if you didn't book yourself in for at least a table either in the Buddha Bar or the Indego.The only one thing I would criticise is the poor internet experience on your TV screen in your room. The browser is ancient and struggles with the most basic sites, which makes the 75 dirham it costs for a day of surfing a rip-off. However, if you travel with your own laptop, you have wi-fi in your room for free.I thoroughly enjoyed my stay, and would like to thank all staff at Grosvenor House for making it such a great experience!	
