Sep 16 2009 	A master class in service and faculties	My partner and I stayed at the Grosvenor House hotel, from the 9th to the 15th September, we were looking for something contemporary and not oppulent dripping in gold. We booked through Expedia and through reading tripadvisor upgraded to the Club room. We are so glad we did, we received a free airport transfer and because we arrived early our room wasn't ready, so after a drink by the pool we checked into our upgraded suite on the 29th floor. We had a lounge, bedroom, kitchen and 2 bathrooms - what a start! As part of the club package you get access to the club lounge, where everything you read is true, canapes (really a running buffet for 2 hours) and enough cocktails/beer/wine to sink a ship. We only paid an extra £20 a night for this upgrade and along with the breakfast - must have received at least £200-£300 worth of food and drink free every day. This of course left money for drink, which at nearly £10 for a glass of wine was a godsend. Yes it does have construction all around the hotel and you can't walk anywhere, but with the spa, pool and Le Meriden over the road - why would you need to? I never even heard much construction noise - even sitting by the pool. My only negative point would be the lack of information on the restaurants and bars within the actual hotel. There wasn't an information pack, nor much signposting around the hotel (we were there 6 nights and only on the 4th night did we realise there was a Gary Rhodes restaurant in the hotel). Of course if you ask; people are happy to tell you, but when you don't know what you're asking for - you may miss out. But whatever you do, don't miss the Buddha bar - food and atmosphere was fab even in Ramadan.	
