en to do it..I also had an issue with my phone where it got water damaged..she was very helpful in trying to help me repair and dry it off..to no avail but the thought was very appreciated.The club next door to the hotel is pretty decent..a chillout bar rather than a rave if that's what you are looking for go to Sanctuary (Palm Island) or 400 (Fairmont Hotel); Buddah Bar is very much a lounge and drink bar with a relaxing sense of music..Bar 44 (top floor) is much more relaxed with some live entertainment and some fantastic views of the city..a variety of interesting alcoholic and non alcoholic cocktails make this bar ideal for all..My only negatives to mention would be the construction work opposite the hotel (consequently an identical hotel to the Grosevenor building) put a little bit of a downer on the view..bar this I cannot think of a single other negative point to mention..I would just like to extend my thanks to all the staff for making me feel very much welcome here it was a delight to stay here	
Aug 19 2009 	5 star hotel	I travelled with my husband early August for our anniversary.After a long flight and having been up for over 24 hours, the serenity of the hotel lounge, the calm efficiency of the staff and the welcome drink of ice tea reassured us we had booked the right hotel.The rooms were comfortable (bed especially), exceptionally clean and serviced what appeared to be 3 times a day. Tea/coffee facilities regularly were replenished as were the bvlgari products that stocked the bathroom. Newspaper on your door every morning, rooms cleaned late morning, cake/savoury snack and fresh fruit and water added in the afternoon, and turn down service in the evening included chocolates and a fresh rose on the pillow.The level of service and the staff at this hotel are exceptional. Two in particular we would like to give credit to. Curtis, by the pool, always welcomed and looked after us, making sure we had plenty of ice, fruit, water and providing us with any knowledge we needed that day. In addition, Joan in the club lounge is a credit to the hotel. She always greeted us for afternoon tea, remembered names which everyone greets you by - they must have a link somewhere), remembered our anniversary, made a fuss of us, sorted restaurant bookings and ensured they made a fuss of us. She was was never overpowering or intimidating. Just there when you needed her.We also used the Spa - Agnes and Leo being our masseurs. Money well spent.We ate at Sloanes every morning for breakfast - go before 10.30 if you wish to avoid waiting/the rush. Again, great service, eggs/omlettes cooked fresh and anyway you want them. All very professional and efficient. You know you're eating fresh food as Tom Egerton seemed to be overseeing the whole operation and taking no prisoners, everything was regularly replenished. The club lounge is worth having - you can get tea, coffee and soft drinks all day, afternoon tea, and then pre dinner drinks. It's also nice to have somewhere to go where you know you can find a seat and get exactly what you want.Evening food: On our anniversary we went to Mezzanine, the Gary Rhodes restaurant. Very upmarket and, though it seems expensive, it's really just comparable to every other restaurant in hotels in Dubai. Lots of tasters were brought to the table and we tested everything from fois gras on gingerbread to eel croquettes and white tomato soup. The food was exceptional, the salmon especially simple and enjoyable given what else is on the menu. At the end of the evening the head chef circulated the tables, chatting to customers and getting feedback. I have never been to a restaurant whereby it was welcomed so much! He has nothing to worry about. We ate at the pizzeria over at the Le Meridien as it was reasonably priced compared to many. Nice pasta, very quiet. However, top tip - your cheapest option is room service. Shock horror! And the food is GOOD!!!!! We did this two evening when we were too knackered to venture anywhere. Excellent tip!If this level of service is what you are after, stay at this hotel in Dubai. They also offer free shuttle buses to Mall of the Emirates and the B=Dubai Mall/Burj Al Arab (tallest building in the world - for now). If you want more than hotels and shopping malls, do NOT visit Dubai. It is 24 hour construction which, luckily unless you sit on your balcony, you will not notice in the confines of hotels or malls. If you are after culture, history, a chance to walk on the beachfront, Dubai does not offer this yet. It may be different in a decades time.One last tip - four days a week, the Jumeriah Mosque offers a tour/talk at 10am. It is 10dhs and well worth it if you need a culture fix. I found it really inspiring and think most people will whatever their religious beliefs.	
