Jun 3 2009 	Outstanding Hotel	I have recently returned from an 8 night stay at the Grosvenor House. Having read so many glittering reviews on Tripadvisor, I had very high expectations, and on the whole I was not let down. I will try to write a balanced review, so that readers can make an informed decision on whether this hotel meets their needs. I have been fortunate enough to stay in the majority of the hotels along the Jumeirah Beach, so feel that I can make a valid comparison on how this hotel fares.The purpose of our visit was leisure. We checked in at 9am, which was not a problem and we were whisked straight up to our room on the 35th floor. We were not offered a welcome drink/towel, but can't stay that we lost any sleep over it. The Club room that we had booked was well appointed with great views over the palm, as well as comfortable beds and nice amenities. As with most UAE hotels, the bathroom was particularly opulent and the Bvlgari toilettries lived up to their reputation! The room was regularly topped up with water, fruit and and a treat from the in house bakery. We took breakfast in both Sloanes and the Club Lounge. Sloanes offers a much wider choice than the Club Lounge, although the lounge is more relaxing. The selection was good in both venues. My only criticism of Sloanes would be that compared to other hotels in Dubai, the fruit selection was not very vast. The best feature of booking a club room was the use of the Club Lounge on the 44th floor. This provided afternoon tea between 3pm and 4.30pm. There was a selection of sandwiches, cakes and scones, which although they did not differ much on a daily basis, were absolutely delicious. The Club Lounge also had a happy hour between the hours of 6-8pm. This offered a selection of hot and cold canapes, as well as complimentary alcoholic drinks. This was an excellent way to start the evening. The staff were very attentive and constantly replenishing our drinks. The quality of the food was outstanding, and we had to restrain ourselves from eating too much to save room for dinner. You could easily make a meal out of the canapes, and I'm sure some people do. My only criticism of the club was when busy there was not much privacy, and the food tended to go pretty quickly. We used the pool facilities most days. The gym and spa facilites were excellent and never too busy. The pool was very nice, although the sun starts getting blocked out from the mid afternoon. The pool staff were generally good, occasionally bringing us water, fruit, and a fruit skewer which was a nice touch. The noise and building work around the pool area is unsightly and quite frankly a problem. We were obviously aware of this before we visited, and whilst it wasn't a major issue, it would have been if we didn't have access to the beach at Le Royal Meridien. I also fear the pool area will be even more shady once the Grosvenor 2 Tower is completed.As mentioned, we favoured the pool and beach at Le Royal Meridien, which is accessed via the free hotel shuttle which takes about 5 minutes. The shuttle didn't seem to run as regularly as suggested, although we rarely had to wait over 20 minutes. The pool and beach here are excellent and well maintained. It is also handy being able to sign food and drink onto your room bill, which saves carrying cash. There was no real sign of the Red Tide phenomonen that we had read about in the press, although by all accounts and can prevent swimming from time to time. It is worth mentioning that Le Royal Meridien is very popular with families, so if screaming kids are not your idea of a romantic or relaxing holiday, it may be better to look elsewhere. Having said that, it didn't bother us in the slightest. The Royal Meridien also provides access to 'The Walk' at Jumeirah Beach Residence, which is a collection of shops and restaurants. This is quite a nice place to for a relaxing stroll in the evenings. The main downside to the Grosvenor House for us was the location. If you are looking for a beach holiday, it can become tedious having to catch the shuttle back and forth, especially if you want to return for afternoon tea and evening drinks. However, if the beach doesn't bother you, then it is difficult to beat the Grosvenor House. Taxis are cheap and plentiful, so getting around is never a problem. The Grosvenor House is a fantastic hotel. Ideal for business, yet equally suitable for a relaxing holiday too. The staff make the hotel what it is, and nothing is too much trouble. The facilities are excellent, and there is a wide choice of dining options. The criticisms I have made are just small ways I think the hotel could improve, and in no way affected my enjoyment of the holiday. I would certainly return and would not hesitate in recommending this hotel to visitors to Dubai.	
