Oct 21 2008	In the land of plenty	The general standards of service and amenity would put to shame most top end business hotels in Europe or the USA.My wife and I made a three night stopover, on the way back from the Maldives, and were most pleased by the ease of the very efficient check in, and the genuine warmth of the welcome.We had the good fortune to be upgraded to a wonderful corner junior suite, (though more like a real suite, with separate living quarters), with a panoramic floor to ceiling curved bay window. The amount of gifts ,sometimes brought twice daily, was impressive indeed, as was the attention to details. On the second evening for example, they left a bottle of Australian Chardonnay in an ice bucket, together with a selection of savoury canapes, to welcome us back into our room. The wine was the same wine that we had ordered in their Oriental restaurant the night before, and had told them that we very much enjoyed it. Such was the attention to details.On that note, their Oriental restaurant proved to be a very nice and intimate place for an evening meal, with gentle live music, consisting of two string-instrument players, dressed in local attires.I did not very much enjoy the Buddha bar restaurant, though an impressive sight , the scale of the place was so immense that a small table for two felt rather lost amidst large surrounding parties.The range of services on offer at the GH is also baffling, and would certainly make all the difference, were this a business trip.For example, I could arrange, with only a twenty minute notice, to have a car and chauffeur to take us to one of the many 'impossible-to-miss' shopping mall .A stylish white Lexus pulled up as soon as we stepped outside the hotel entrance, and the very nice and discreet driver took us to where we wanted, and had obviously just waited for us during the whole two hours we were there , to promptly reappear at the meeting point we had arranged, to help us with our shamefully overloaded shopping bags. He smoothly drove us back in the ice-cooled car, through Dubai's traffic jams. And this princely service only cost in all about 50 US dollars. To rejuvenate from such busy days, the hotel has an excellent indoor spa, where all possible treatments are available, again without any fastidiously long advanced booking, in fact, you can pretty much just turn up on a whim. The standard of service were, once again, outstanding. During a manicure, they will of course offer various refreshements, but also give you a complimentary shoe shine.I must also mention that we had decided to stay on the executive floor, for a small nightly supplement, to use the compimentary bar on the top floor, for the occasional coffee, or pre-dinner drink.In fact, the bar featured a sumptuous buffet at all time of the day, often replenished with luxurious offerings to enjoy with a chilled glass of delicious champagne.It was unfortunate, however, to be surrounded by some of my British compatriots, who seem to be more used to a £4.99-eat-all-you-can-buffet, back home. As the chav boyfriends would accumulate drinks on their table, (beer and champagne), their overweight girlfriends, enthralled by the cornucopia on offer, would elbow their way to pile up the saussages and the smoked salmon, on their plates, blurting out &quot;Oooo, lovely!&quot;Those same people would of course never be seen for their inclusive breakfast, as they were all in the main restaurant, where much larger and greasyer foods could be found. This meant that on the three mornings we were there, my wife and I had the whole executive lounge all to ourselves, where it is a very pleasent place to start the day, with ample choices for breakfast, with cold cuts, fruit skewers and top quality cereals.Perfect service from the sweet and professional Asian and Indian team.In the evening, for a night cap, the main bar on the top floor, (opposite the executive lounge), is a fun place, with excellent cocktails, and jazzy live music. Often crowded, it is nice just to sit back in a comfortable armchair, and watch a wonderful array of flashy polyester evening dresses go by.In conclusion, Dubai really is a place like no other, an experience I would recommend anyone to do at least once in their lives. And the Grosvenor House hotel is, near enough, the perfect base to do that.	
