Mar 8 2008 	Will be back!	I spent 4 nights in the GH with my husband in February as a stopover, before travelling on to Australia. I can only confirm all the raving reviews below. Being a frequent traveller (and admittedly quite a fussy one!), I always put much emphasis on the accommodation (even if I 'only sleep there'). As far as I could tell from the feedback, the GH ticked all the boxes so my expectations were high. I can honestly say, it did not disappoint on any level. The service was excellent, I can not speak highly enough of the drivers, check-in staff, waiters, housekeepers etc. Everyone we spoke to was very helpful and friendly. The hotel has a light, airy feel with big open spaces, wide corridors, beautiful furniture (even in the public bathrooms!).The room itself is not overly large, however, has got everything you might need. Loved the little extras, like the extensive stationery, Bulgari toiletries, the daily canapes, fruit etc . (The evening chocolates are to die for!) All the amenities are very high quality. We had a spectacular view from our room on the 41st floor overlooking the Palm and the Burj Al Arab in the distance. Just what we came for! Although we had a Club room, with all the extras, we found that it's difficult to take advantage of all it has to offer when you are busy sightseeing etc. The breakfast on the 44th floor was nice, but much smaller selection than in the main buffet (which was outstanding!) and the tables are far too low to eat comfortably. It has a lounge/bar set up and really that is what it is. Very nice in the evening for pre-dinner drinks and hot and cold snacks, if you manage to make it on time. Only slightly disappointed with the rather small drink selection there, however, the atmosphere and service made up for it. I don't regret paying the premium, however, next time will probably go without as we simply didn't have the time to make the most of it.We tried both the Indian and Turkish restaurants in the hotel, both exeptional. Also visited the Buddha Bar, but found it way too crowded and smoky, impessive decor and good music though, so might be more suitable if you are out for a few drinks with a group of friends.The weather was very pleasant during our stay (2-6 Feb), but not quite hot enough to enjoy the facilities of the Meridien on the beach front. We were invited there to a cocktail party one evening, so had a quick look anyway. It is more a resort style hotel, suitable for families just wanting to relax.We have been planning to visit Dubai for a while and had the impression that a few days would be enough to take it all in. Well, in our opinion, 3 days could only give a taste of the ever-changing city. Won't even mention the cranes, yes they are very much part of the skyline, however, it is a well known fact, so don't say you are surprised! We were never disturbed by constraction noise while in the hotel, even though the nearest one was less than 100 yards away. I found it quite amusing to watch the workers up high...At the end of the day, they make Dubai what it is today, a fast developing wonder in the middle of the desert.I am already planning my next trip, really looking forward to seeing the progress.	
Feb 29 2008	An Outstanding Hotel in a Good Location	Located adjacent to the Marina, this member of the Le Meridien family is an excellent luxury hotel, firmly in place with the Park Hyatt, Shangri-La, Ritz Carlton, Fairmont and the rest. Currently the area is a construction zone – like the rest of Dubai – so there is a fair amount of noise. However, from my club-level room on the 35th floor, this only seemed noticeable during the day.The room I had was beautifully appointed, with a large amount of closet and storage space, workdesk (with free wired internet), wall-mounted LCD television and wrap-around balcony. The large bathroom included a tub and separate walk-in shower plus toilet and bidet. As with all the rooms in the hotel, views were to the west overlooking the Palm Jumeirah… though there is another tower under construction between this hotel and the water, so the view as it is currently will likely be quite different a year from now.The service throughout the hotel is impeccible. When I needed help from guest services for reservations and other information, it was provided promptly and accurately.I found the value provided with the club-level room to be worth the extra cost. The lounge on the 44th floor provided food (that was okay to pretty good) most of the day, though I found the wireless internet there to be intermittent for unknown reasons. I had a late night departure from the airport, so the club provided an excellent retreat for the several hours I needed to kill after my (requested and granted) 4 p.m. checkout. Of course, the free airport transfers are also a big part of the value in the club-level rooms.I had dinner in the Buddha Bar one night. Again, the service was outstanding and the food very good. I tried several of the sushi offerings and found the quality to be very good, but with little imagination in the preparation. Coming from southern California, where there are many outstanding sushi restaurants, I would not recommend Buddha Bar to others who have a high level of expectation in the areas of creativity and diversity with regard to the menu. Nonetheless, it was a satisfying dining experience.	
Feb 27 2008 	Slick hotel	We had a 3 day stopover en route from the Far East to the UK at this hotel. We booked a standard room, no frills. You really dont need more than this - you get all the luxuries - Bulgari treats in the bathroom (fill your luggage up!! - how cheap am I!?) Chocolates and fruit every day. Separate shower with power shower, gorgeous comfy bed. The hotel is fairly new so everything is to a very good standard. They were offering half board to entice travellers to stay in the centre of the worlds largest building site. The food was excellent! Yes, there is building work everywhere, and the view from the balcony was rubble, cranes, diggers, but its actually quite fascinating seeing just what is emerging in this city. You could see 'Atlantis' from our hotel. It was pretty much on the horizon, but its colossal. Everything is huge, everything has to be bigger and better than the last one built. Don't complain about it when you know its happening before you travel there - choices can be made - there is enough publicity to tell you what to expect, and you wont be disappointed!!The hotel pool, although beautiful, was a disappointment, as the sun is shaded after late morning, simply because of the high buildings. However, you can then take the shuttle bus accross the road to Le Royal Meridian, to use their pool facilities, which are 'on the beach' and extremely nice. So, you get the best of both worlds by staying here - the sleek modern new Grosvenor, and the lovely pool, gardens, beach area at LRM.Would stay here again, but next time there will not be a view from the room, as there was a second hotel tower being built right infront of the current one. Shame.	
Feb 22 2008 	Luxury	We stayed in this hotel whilst on our honeymoon. We stayed for 3 nights as a stop gap on the way back home.Well where do I start, and what do I say. This hotel is fantastic, sheer luxury. I havent stopped talking about this hotel since we came back.We were picked up at the airport by private transfer which we had arranged ourselves through our travel agents for al the destinations we went to, however I know that if you book this hotel they arrange to pick you up. We arrived in the early hours of the morning (5am). we had just been to Kuala Lumpar and were exhausted. The check-in was really quick and as it was our honeymoon we were upgraded to a suite. The suite was absolutely stunning, I couldnt stop taking pictures of it.The hotel is really modern and the staff could not have been any more helpful and were really happy to assist you. The restaurant staff were great. We were able to use the club lounge between the hours of pm-8pm where the drink was free and there were snacks. It is definately worth upgrading to use this facility. the only thing I'd say bad about it was that the service was quite slow. We had also stayed in the Shangrai-La in Kuala Lumpar and it was self-service with the drinks so it was really good.The hotel has a small pool which was great and it was quite quiet when we were there in August. There was pool service and you were provided with ice cold water, cold towels, fruit etc. We went over to the sister hotel Le Royal Meridian to use the pool there (a shuttle bus takes you over to it due to the construction works you cant walk over) it has a much bigger pool but I felt it was too busy with lots of kids there. As it was our honeymoon I prefered the quieter pool at the Grosvenor.I wouldnt go back to Dubai in august as it was far too hot. I like to sunbath but it was actually unbearable and you just wanted to go back into the air conditioned buildings. If we ever go back I'd definatley stay in this hotel.	
