Nov 17 2007 	Lovely hotel marred by 3 hour check in	We were in Dubai for a weekend. Because of two different arrival times (1.30am for me, 5.30am for my partner) we spent the first night in the Le Meridien Dubai, with the next two nights in Grosvenor House.The experience started well with a prompt pick up from Le Meridien at 11am. We got to Grosvenor House a little before 12. The Reception staff told us that our room was not ready, but took us up to Leaves to have a drink while we waited. Foolishly, we took this to mean it would be a short wait. The staff at Leaves were very nice, giving us a complimentary tea, and then a free lunch when we were still waiting. But they were unable to get any information from reception. Several phone calls gleaned such useful info as &quot;there are quite a few people checking out right now, but they don't know when your room will be ready&quot; (this at 1.30pm). Finally just before 3pm, still being told in Leaves that our room was not ready, we went to reception. We did then get into a room (not the one originally assigned). But the day was pretty much wasted by then. If only they had said when we first checked in that our room was not ready, and that it would be a long time, but we could go over to the beach while we were waiting, I would have given them top marks. Or even if they'd said we could check in at 3pm, we'd have gone shopping. Anything but being kept waiting after our very long journeys.As other reviews mentioned, the area is a building site, but that didn't bother us - the shuttle bus to the beach was fine. The beach, pool, and pool bar at the Royal Meridien were great. The room was also lovely - very comfy bed, fabulous TV and entertainment system, we had a fantastic view (although out on the balcony, the construction noise was a bit intrusive, the room itself was quiet), and the bathroom was great. But 3 hours being kept waiting and fobbed off out of a 48 hour trip is too high a price to pay.We had a club room, so access to the lounge. Evening drinks and afternoon tea were very good. Breakfast had interesting variety but the food heaters didn't work very well - it was cold even when we ate at 6.30 on the day we left. We tried to get into Indego one evening, but it was full, so we had room service both nights, which was excellent.November in Dubai is obviously high season - rooms at our usual hotels were hard to find, which is why we 'treated' ourselves to GH, and we each had to wait over an hour in line at immigration. The weather was lovely - much more comfortable than previous visits in hotter months - but I think we'll stick to low season for short breaks.	
