Oct 2 2007	Great Expectations Lead To Disappointment	I've stayed at a number of high end hotels in Dubai; Crown Plaza, Hyatt Regency, Hilton, Sheraton Creek, Radison, Habtoor Grand, Fairmont, etc...On my next trip to Dubai I would prefer any of the above to Grosvenor house. It wasn't particularly terrible, just that things weren't quite up to par. The hotel staff seemed very kind and well meaning, but lacking in capability.These may seem like small nitpicks but they really are inconveniences that just wouldn't happen at other hotels. One or two is understandable but once a pattern developes it's clear that Grosvenor has some service shortcomings.Specifically:(1) At any other hotel I can make a quick remark to ANY staff member on my way out that I would like my room cleaned. At Grosvenor this resulted in the &quot;Guest Services&quot; desk telling me no, I would need to talk to the reception instead and then when I did return to my room 6 hours later it was still uncleaned.(2) At the business center I had a document scanned and saved to memory stick. One of the pages was scanned twice and the other not at all. I returned to get the error fixed and was once again given an incomplete scan. Only on the third time, when I went to physically watched as they scanned, did they get it right. Also they were unable to incorporate the scans in to a PDF or word document and I was instead left with 15 separate and large picture files.(3) Laundry pressing. Was told that pressing dropped picked up during the evening would not be ready till the next evening. Most hotels offer next morning service. I did have them pick up two piles of clothes, one for next morning and one for next evening. The clothes returned for morning were a mix of the two piles. ie. The clothes I needed were not ready(4) Internet access was sometimes slow to the point of being unusable, having to attempt 5 times to open an e-mail. 500ms latency and 17% packet loss to the US for you computer types.(5) I woke one morning to find my computer had shut down during the night. Seems some of the wall power sockets had stopped working while I slept. A call to the front desk saying &quot;the socket where I plug my computer in has no power&quot; but only got the response &quot;internet no work?&quot; Eventually this did get fixed but it was fairly representative of staff english comprehension. I once called to ask for my room service plates, etc... to be taken away and got the response &quot;you want room service?&quot;(6) Disturbances. It seems like there was a knock on the door every few minutes for something. Even with the no-cleaning sign on, someone still knocked to ask when I want cleaning and I told them &quot;I'll call when I need it&quot;, then one hour later someone called on the phone to ask the same question (and got the same answer), and after thirty minutes, another phone call with the question again. Stop pestering!I could go on but I'm sure you can see the trend.Also there was heavy contruction going on right outside my balconey and the room itself was pretty unremarkable and somewhat small. If you want to stay in this area, choose the Habtoor Grand. Otherwise go for Sheraton or Hilton Creek in the beautiful downtown area.If you want an effortless, perfect stay, choose somewhere else.	
Sep 25 2007 	Beautiful Hotel but marred by construction	We have literally just returned from the Grosvenor House, and like many of the other reviews found the service and rooms to be faultless. Not surprisingly (just like other reviews) we were up-graded to a Suite on the 18th Floor. The Suite consisted of a Cloakroom, Kitchen, Dinning Area (large plasma screen + Bose sound system), Lounge, Bedroom (massive bed + plasma screen) and large bathroom. Fresh fruit and canape's were delivered each day, and then chocolates and a rose were included as part of the turn-down service.Breakfast was included in our package, and we can honestly say it's probably the best spread we've ever seen!A 24 Hour Butler ensured total perfection from a Service point of view; indeed every member of staff went out of their way to make sure we were 100% happy with our stay. On a slightly negative point, we paid an additional sum for lounge access, but found this didn't give true value for money, as it is too small for the number of hotel guests - we were turned away on 2 evenings due to lack of seating. Bar 44 and the Buddha Bar are certainly worth a visit. However, we found Indigra Indian Restaurant a real disappointment and hugely expensive.The main reason for not giving the Grosvenor House 5/5 is due to the small pool which is surrounded by sky-scrapers and on-going construction work (you can't hear the noise inside, but it's very loud outside!). Yes, there is a shuttle service which takes you over to Le Royal Meridien, but again, construction work mars the beach as 'Tonka Trucks' and Dredgers are constantly moving backwards and forwards delivering boulders to a man-made Marina being built very close by. We were in Dubai 2 years ago, and expected building work, but admit to being absolutely taken aback by the scale of work going on around the Grosvenor House or 'New Dubai' as it's now being called. If you enjoy lazing around a pool or on the beach then we certainly can't recommend the Grosvenor House for the time being - you'll be very disappointed!Our recommendations for shopping are: Madinat Souq, IBN Batatta Mall and Karama Souq (fake handbags and watches).Recommendations for restaurants: Zheng He's (Mina A'Salam), Bice (Hilton Jemeirah), Toscano (Madinat Souq) and Le Splendido (Ritz Carlton). For a cheaper meal without alcohol we enjoyed the Royal Orchid (Thai/Chinese) on Marina Walk.	
Sep 21 2007 	Greatest Modern Hotel in Dubai	Our first trip in Dubai led us to stay in this Starwood property Grosvenor House thanks to great advice we had from Trailfinders. We stayed there 4 nights from Sunday the 9th until 13th September. The check-in was very quick and one of the receptionist came with us to show us our room. In fact it wasn't a room. We were upgraded to have an apartment on the 8th floor instead. We were so lucky. The hotel is split between hotel rooms and apartments. Elevators lead to rooms, others to apartments only. Both products have a separate reception and concierge as well. The apartment we had was very functional with a fully equipped kitchen with complementary tea and coffee. A living - dining room with the latest technology available on a plasma screen (video on demand, music on demand, international channels, Internet, ...). We have a huge bathroom with a separate shower with toilets. Another toilet room was near the living room as well. Our bedroom was also equipped with this plasma screen with same technology. Both bedroom and living room were giving you a view of the street side with all the building in construction and the one finished. Windows must have been soundproofed as we were never disturbed by the noise. We were very delighted by the comfort of the king size bed. Matrice, duvet and pillows were so comfy that we need to ask the hotel where they found those to equip our house in London. Every day we had complimentary fruits and petits fours + water bottles. In the bathroom, all amenities were provided by Molton Brown. I have heard that in the hotel, amenities are from Bulgari with their superb fragrance Thé Blanc. The hotel has plenty of restaurants to choose from. We tried the best buffet I ever come across at Sloanes where you eat oysters, sushis, lobster on the grill, ribeye steak and so many dishes. The dessert buffet is also very impressive with a chocolate fondue. Breakfast is also served at Sloanes and is very good and full of choices. On the last night, we tried the Indian restaurant Indego which is probably one the best Indian restaurant I have ever eaten. Don't expect the usual Korma or Madras but more original and innovative dishes from a clever and talented chef. There is so much to say about this hotel. One more thing, the hotel is not on the beachfront. But you can take a bus provided by the hotel who will take you to the sister hotel Le Méridien Beach &amp; Resort and then take the facility of the hotel (it's just a 3 mins drive). At the hotel, they will provide you a towel and you have full access to both swimming pools and the beach.Finally, the hotel has also outside the Budha Bar recreated which quite impressive and very busy at night.If you are looking for a modern hotel with comfortable rooms in Dubai, Grosvenor House is for you whether you are Leisure or Business.	
