Jun 25 2007 	Top Class Hotel	From the moment we arrived in the Grosvenor House we knew that we on a winner. When we arrived (overnight Flight, got in at 6am) we were upgraded to a suite, given a complementary stay in the Spa until the room as ready and a free buffet breakfast. I have to say that things only got better from there!!! The hotel itself is fantastic, ultra modern, and very cool. All of the staff, seem to know your name from the first day??? There are a total of 10 Restaurants, our favorite being Mezzanine (French and close to Michelin star quality). The room its self was the best we have every stayed in, Kitchen, large bedroom, and a lounge + dining room and two 50” plasma’s. When staying in the suite you get complementary treats every day (Fruit, Pastries and chocolates). At the top of the hotel is Bar 44 (44th floor), a very hip and trendy place to get a drink before you head out. The views of the marina and the plam in the distance are unbelievable, but be warned though, the alcohol in all of Dubai is very expensive and wine excessively so… The pool area is again excellent, but quiet small. You get a free bottle of iced water, a face spray and fresh fruit when you go to sunbath each day. Some of the other reviews talk about shading, from the buildings but this is not a problem as you just move with the sun. Anyway you will not be able to last in the summer sun more that 2-3 hours. Also you can go to the Sister hotel (Le Meridian) about half a mile away. Which has a much larger pool area and is also beach fronted…there is a free shuttle bus to and from each hotel every few minutes…Lastly I would just like to say that the Dubai holiday and stay in the Grosvenor was the best holiday I have ever been on. A true and excellent 5* hotel.	
Jun 21 2007 	Wow practically perfect	From the moment you arrive you can tell that service is a priority. There were at least a dozen valet lined up ready to help. The fresh flowers everywhere including the staff members was one sign of the quality of this hotel. The entire hotel is modern, clean, and new. The spacious room had a plasma tv, wood accents, and a marble bathroom with a tub fit for 2. The towels were so big they could have substituted as sheets for the bed. We felt special because every time we arrived back at the room there were gifts(chocolates, fruit, pastries, etc.) and notes all personalized. This is for a standard room, I can imagine what the club room guests receive. We did go to Bar H on the 44th floor. Overpriced(3 drinks=$60) and too loungy, better for an older crowd. The pools, facilities, and service at the sister Meridien were fantastic. It happens to be significantly more expensive for a room there without the modern design. I was most pleasantly surprised by the beach. White sand, crystal clear water. Don't get put off by the water temperature. It gets cooler, but not much deeper about 20 yards in. If you are going to stay in Dubai and are slightly concerned about a budget, stay here, hands down.	
Jun 20 2007	Fantastic !	Although we were advised not to stay at this hotel due to the fact it was in the middle of a building site, the reviews from this site convinced us otherwise.I have not booked any travel through a tour operator for several years but surprisingly, Kuoni were by far the cheapest for our holiday.We were not disappointed. The level of service was incredible. We had booked a Club room and for an extra £15 per person per day, we certainly received fantastic value for money. We received breakfast, afternoon tea and access to Club Lounge, where canapes and alcohol, ncuding champagne, were served free from 1800 til 2000 each evening. As alcohol is expensive in the hotels, this saved us a lot.We had a gorgeous room and a balcony which could hold 50 people no problem. Each evening, we received the usual chocs, a rose, canapes, water, candles. The beds, duvets and pillows were soooo comfortable we could have spent half the holiday there.We went to the Meridien's beach and pool one day but it was full of screaming kids etc, so we preferred the Grosvenor pool even though a building was under construction above it.We ate at Sloanes and Budda Bar. Both were excellent. Didnt have a bad meal anywhere. At at Trader Vics at Madinat, Prime Rib and Seafood market in Royal Meridien, Go West in Jumierah Beach, Blue Eliphant (Al Bustana Rotana at airport). All were great.	
Jun 11 2007	Staying here as we write	I am writing this review whilst staying in the hotel, it is fantastic.On arrival we were told that our room was not ready but not to worry as we were being upgraded to a suite. the suite has a living room, two bathrooms, two 42&quot; plasma's and all the other bits you expect to find with a hotel of this class. the staff are exceptionally friendly and will go above and beyond to make sure your requests are dealt with.the restaurants are good if a bit pricey, a single plate of lamb kebabs (Ottoman's) is around £20 and ice cream £2 a scoop! a bottle of beer is reasonable at around £3 and a cocktail is approx £10. As for the beach, pool, etc you can use the shuttle bus (every 3-4 mins) to take you to the meridien across the road, you really need to take the shuttle bus as it is not accesible from the GHH due to building work around the hotel ( the area is developing fast and every other building is still in the process of being built, but on'tlet this put you off as you cannot hear a thing in your room) overall the hotel is modern and extremely clean,it is in a good location. The rooms are spacious and quiet, bits and bobs that may be of use: you will have to put a deposit of £150 to cover the mini bar, restaurants etc. a taxi from the airport costs approx £10-£15 and are metered ask for an upgrade to a club room, you never know it may work. if you want to eat in the restaurants you must book a day or two before. the dress code is smart casual, No shorts, vests or trainers etc in the lounges, bars or restaurants.If you want to eat at Burj Al Arab it it better if you book before leaving home. they can sometime be fully booked for weeks in advance.If you want to eat there try and get a table at al mahara as the sky bar is supposedly meant to be a bit dodgy, although I cannot say for sure because we haven't eaten there.Have a good time in Dubai and make sure you bring lots of cash, it is friggin expensive if you go shopping in the touristy areas like the mall, hotels etc.	
Jun 7 2007 	Five Star all the way	Having sold the Grosvenor House a few times as a travel agent I was quite excited about staying there as the reviews here were so good and feedback from our customers was good. We went for the Club Room option which was really worth it- the lounge on the top floor for the club diners is quite small- one night we went across to Bar 44 but to be honest we preferred it there as the views were great. Our room was on the 35th floor overlooking the Habtoor and I can honestlysay we couldnt hear a thing from indoors (re: building works) and being so far up you hear a few beeps if you stand on your balcony but that's all. The pool at the hotel isn't ideal, it's shady by 2pm and is overlooked by a building site with interested builders checking out the clientele! But most people get the free shuttle to the Royal Meridien over the road which has 3 pools and the beach. The hotel itself is spotless, there must be 1 staff member to every client and the ambience was relaxed and unstuffy, with nothing too much trouble. The little things like chocolates and fresh fruits in your room were lovely- the beds are huge and so comfy. The breakfast is the largest and most eclectic mix I have seen and I had dinner at the Buddha Bar which was absolutely divine and not too expensive. Overall I wouldn't have any problem recommending this hotel, it is something very special and even though the Royal Meridien is it's 5 star sister hotel, the clientele and atmosphere at the Grosvenor is much better. You'll be sorry to leave.	
