May 13 2007 	The new standard in Dubai	My new favourite in Dubai. Just spent 5 nights there in a club room - great interior to the hotel, funky and contemporary compared to a lot of the hotels in Dubai which tend to be a bit gaudy in the way they are decorated. Room was great, big plasma TV, Bulgari cosmetics, luxurious bathroom.Club rooms are well worth the extra - don't know if they are any different in decor etc. but the club lounge on the 44th floor is very goo - all day access to snacks/beverages, and they do breakfast there, plus afternoon tea with amazing array of all you can eat cream cakes! In the evening it is free booze for 2 hours from 630-830 - a worthwhile perk in Dubai where booze is hideously expensive. We paid about £150 for 2 people to upgrade to a club so about £30/day, and we got that back in booze alone by each having 2 glasses of champagne as an aperitif each evening before dinner.Staff are very attentive through the entire hotel, and restaurants were superb on every occasion. Also has a great spa, and the best gym of any hotel in Dubai I have come across.Downsides? Well the pool area is not the best - a new tower is being constructed literally feet away and there are always hordes of builders leering across at the women by the pool. And there is no beach. But to counteract this, you do get access to the facilities at the Royal Meridien Beach Resort and Spa, and it is about 200m away with a frequent shuttle service (you couldnt actually walk the distance due to roads and construction). The integrationwith the Royal Meridien is seamless - you can charge to your room at all their bars/restaurants so don't need to worry about cash for purchases there. Previously we have stayed at the One and Only Arabian Court and the Royal Meridien Beach Resort and Spa. Until this visit, we thought the Arabian Court was unsurpassable but after 5 days in the Grosvenor we then had 5 days at the Arabian Court and both wished we had stayed at the Grosvenor as the Arabian Court has gone alarmingly downhill since we stayed there in January this year - the customer services manager acknowledged that they were struggling due to lots of new staff as turnover has been very high.Next time we go to Dubai we will return to the Grosvenor rather than the Arabian Court - and perhaps also try the Al Qasr at Madinat which is the only one with the potential to match the Grosvenor.	
