Mar 16 2007 	very good but some drawbacks	Good points:Sun beds - There is never a shortage here or at the sister hotel, the Royal MeridienClub room - Probably worth upgrading to if you like unlimited drinks (we had champagne) between 6pm and 8pm, exclusive breakfast (more choice in the main restaurant, Sloane's though), high tea and all day soft drinks, tea, coffee and cakes. View from the club lounge is great too. If you don't drink a lot, you may not consider the upgrade worthwhile.Upgrade - Don't expect one. We were offered one at £600 for 10 nights, not free like some others.Shopping - For bargains, avoid the malls and head for Bur Dubai or Karama if you don't mind being harrassed by over zealous traders. Shopping malls are about the same as UK prices.Rooms - Lovely! Service - First class.Taxis - Cheap and abundant. We spend 1.5 hrs getting from the hotel to the Hyatt for dinner and it cost under £10.Bad points:Noise - There is a lot of building work go on around the hotel 24/7 so if you are a light sleeper, beware. I slept for only a few hours a night because of constant building noise.Clientele - This is mostly a business hotel. Next time I'll stay at the sister hotel, Royal Meridien as this is on the beach and more suited to leisure visitors. I felt a little underdressed at times.Walking - You can do virtually no walking around the hotel. Even getting to the sister hotel which is 400 metres, requires a (frequent and courtesy) bus ride as there are no paths!Traffic - if you want to eat towards the city centre (towards the airport) between 8 and 9pm, allow 1.5 hrs to get there from the hotel as traffic is very heavy from 6-9pm.Food - Avoid the revolving resturant at the Hyatt. Overpriced and food not good. We liked: Buddha Bar, Mezzanine, Fusion.	
Mar 16 2007 	Excellent will be better when the building works have finished	Stayed here in Nov 2006. Both late 20's well travelled couple.My job has the bonus of getting to stay in some great 5 star hotels around the world. This was a personal holiday and after spending 4 nights at The Grand Hyatt in Oman we arrived for 5 nights in Dubai. Was last here in March 2005 for work and the building work was bad then. Coming back now was even worse. This is building work like you have never seen before. You can't turn around without seeing a crane. The hotel is situated in the West Marina about 20mins from the centre of Dubai. The exterior and interior and a sight to behold. Checked in whilst sitting on a beautiful sofa and a drink in our hand. Our Butler (guest services in reality) took us up to our room. We were lucky enough to be upgraded to an apartment on the west side of the hotel (the hotel is divided into hotel rooms and apartments). Huge room (bigger than our 1 bed flat in London), had to check with reception that I wasn't paying the wrong price for it!The attention the staff give you is second to none. I especially had a lot of time for the manager of the Gallery bar who spent ages chatting with us and at the same time keep the drinks flowing for the other guests. Bar 44 is a great place to spend the evening looking out across the city. If you get a club room then you can use the other part of the bar which the public can't drink in. The only thing is that it does get very busy as the night goes on and is very popular with non residents. Breakfast is a large buffet style with a range from fruits, cereals and full english.The pool is let down by two things. Its location on the east side of the hotel and the building works. The hotel building casts a shadow across the whole pool area from around 2pm onwards and unless you move around the the small suntrap on the beach side thats all the sun you will see for the rest of the day! The 24 hour building work is a bit of a pain too. When we arrived we looked down on a development, by the time we left they were looking down on us! You can't hear the noise though once you are inside. You can use the sister hotel Le Meridian which has a large pool and beach area. Free shuttle bus operates from the front of the hotel. Takes about 1 minute but because of all the building works around you can't walk it.Great service, great hotel, great food and drink. Will be great in 5 years when all the buildings in the Marina have been built.	
