Feb 25 2007	A wonderful experience at Grosvenor House	From the moment we entered Grosvenor House it was a wonderful experience. Be prepared for the fact that the hotel is right in the middle of a massive building site (like much of Dubai) but once inside you would never know. On the way to the hotel Dubai looked space age and the rocket shape of the hotel fitted the landscape perfectly! Like many people have said we were upgraded to a Suite instead of the Club Room we had booked and the additional benefits of Club are a must. The Suite had 2 large plazma TVs, a stunning bathroom with Bulgari accessories, the most comfortable bed I've ever slept in, a separate lounge area with huge circular panoramic windows over the building site, fascinating in itself, (plus the marina and beach I must add!) and an attached kitchen with fridge. Fresh flowers, fresh fruit and small cakes brought daily were nice touches and access to the Club lounge meant that we never went short. Unlimited drinks and canapes between 6pm and 8pm meant that we overdosed on champage and were so well dined that dinner wasn't esential. However, we did eat in Buddah Bar one night, an experience not to be missed for the excellent food and wonderful atmosphere. £100 for a bottle of wine and two courses each was very good value. Another good experience was the Desert Safari booked through the hotel - a must if you want to see camels!! The free courtesy car, part of the Club Room package, saw us back to the airport in style. Frequent transfers to Le Royal Meridien meant that we could have the beach as well as the luxury of the Grosvenor. Le Royal Meridien is far more family based but we wanted to escape families and lots of children so as more of a business hotel, the Grosvenor fitted our criteria perfectly. A leisurely breakfast on the terrace was worth relaxing over with a huge array of excellent food, the best I've ever seen for a hotel breakfast and it stayed open until 11.30am. All in all, a perfect choice for a five night break in Dubai. This is a hotel that clearly has an outstanding Hotel General Manager as the attention to detail in all aspects of the hotel put it right at the top of the class for quality with service that is never intrusive but always to hand. What a shock to return to Britain and the depression of Heathrow. After Dubai taxis which were so modern and cheap, it cost £38 for two single tickets on National Express from Heathrow to Gatwick on a dirty coach - that says it all!!	
Feb 25 2007 	Overhyped	This is a good hotel but some people seem to either have rose tinted glasses or do not usually stay in luxury hotels. The service is generally very good but can be erratic. We were not offered a drink when we arrived and our key card did not work until the next day. This meant that we had to go via reception every time we returned to our room. The bed was sometimes not turned down and we missed out on cakes some nights. The breakfast selection is fantastic but after nine the hot food is not hot. We ate at Sloanes one evening and again the choice was fantastic but self service gave it an 'all inclusive' feel. Indigo and Mezzanine restaurants were very good but not exceptional and were on the expensive side. The worst aspect of this hotel is its position. It is absolutely surrounded on all sides by 24 hr construction. You have a balcony but you cant use it because of the noise and dust. Dont even think about 'relaxing' by the pool. I am amazed that people have accepted the 24 hr construction as being part of Dubai. We paid over £300 (maybe too much!) a night with Trailfinders and we did not expect the construction to be so bad, particularly because of the glossed over comments on this site. I have never expeienced anywhere like it and I agree with a previous reveiwer that Dubai does not have soul and it has a mass of high rises. Moans over and now the good. The sun shines, the service is above average, it is exceptionally clean, everything works and the food is of a high standard. The Grosvenor House is a good hotel and I have been picky to give perspective to the high marks it has been given. I will probably go back to see how well the mass of construction has been finished off and to see the sunshine in winter. You have to accept it for what it is but I doubt I will ever be able to say 'I love Dubai'.	
Feb 22 2007 	Building work at The Grosvenor	We have just returned from staying at The Grosvenor House, Dubai for three nights on our return from the Maldives. The hotel is very nice, it really can't be faulted in any way, the staff are polite and courteous and the rooms are excellent - as is the food. Our only problem was with the actual position of the hotel. To get to the beach you need to use the hotel courtesy bus which takes you to the sister hotel over the road (Le Meridien). It is impossible to walk there yourself because of the extensive building work taking place to three sides of The Grosvenor. The only outdoor area to sit is around the pool due there being no gardens.We saw an earlier report mentioning building work and queried this point with the hotel. We were told the noise was minimal and that sound barriers are erected to counteract it. On arrival we were dismayed to find that the building work is on three sides of the hotel causing traffic chaos at busy times. The noise from the pile drivers could also be heard over the air conditioning and sound barriers were not erected. The work also takes place on a shift basis so continues more or less twenty four hours a day. We didn't sit around the pool area partly because it looks out over the building sites. The sea view room we were given (a suite which was very nice) sadly overlooked the building work and although the sea could be seen it was in fact through the Habtoor and Meridien hotels. The area in front of the Marina is also being developed.We were unable to walk to the Marina due to the only footpath by the hotel being cordonned off in both directions.I am sure that once the building work is completed things will be much better but we did feel confined at this hotel. I must stress however that the hotel is superb.	
