May 18 2006	Number 1 Hotel	Being a travel agent I'm fortunate enough to have travelled extensively. I have stayed in Dubai before but never at the Grosvenor, what a find!This Hotel is the best I have ever stayed in, their staff are extremely well trained and are attentive, well mannered and make you feel so special (even down to remembering your name) that anything less now will be a disappointment! One can replicate the building and furnishings but not the staff!I stayed in a club room for a small extra which gave me access to the club lounge on the 44th floor, again the staff made this a fabulous experience. The breakfast buffet was very good for such an intimate lounge and the pre dinner canapes excellent. Alchoholic drinks in the evening (included in the room cost) flowed freely as did the champagne and several evenings we missed dinner but happily moved over to Bar 44 across the hallway for fantastic views of Downtown Dubai and 'The Burj'. This is a piano bar with 360 degree views of the Marina and Dubai, again the staff are happy, courteous and very good at keeping you supplied with drinks!Downstairs the 6 restaurants provide menus from around the world, the Indian is a modern fusiion of what we are used to at home and authentic recipes. Beautiful calm surroundings and delicious food. The Buddha Bar (which you have to go outside the Hotel to enter) is a buzzy, exciting experience, which is full of young beautiful people having fun. The eclectic music and atmosphere enhances the setting and food, all under the gazeful watch of a 30 foot high Buddha. Very theatrical, go see for yourself!!The spa is tranquil and full of dark woods and water features, the staff are just as good as you would expect now and dont let the side down. Only one disappoinment, if travelling with a Husband or male friend - they cant join you in the steam room or jacuzzi as there is a male/female divide!! One might feel this is a positive thing though?Outside by the pool all is well, the staff provide you with towels, fruit juice, water and skewered fruit and you can chill until your hearts content! The sun does move behind the Hotel by early afternoon but one can then go over to the Grosvenors sister hotel (just across the road, transported by hotel shuttle) and use their beach club.There is building work going on around you and very, very occasionaly you can hear the few odd bumps and knocks but by now you are so relaxed and well looked after that you dont care! Actually my Husband found the 'goings on' around us interesting! We did walk down to the marina one afternoon and found ourselves amongst the 'locals' having coffee and tea with their friends and families. Lots of cafes, restaurants and expensive boats.Apart from being cosseted by this lovely hotel there is of course the rest of Dubai, downtown has the creek, crossed by an Abra and ending up in the souks is an experience not to be missed. Dinner in the desert after being thrown around in a 4 wheeled drive over the dunes is another experience, bit touristy though, especially when your hosts bring out the camels and encourage you to hop onboard!! The shopping mall with the ski slope which makes you feel youre in Kloisters and the beautiful modern architecture surrounding you, which even if you dont like you must appreciate the enthusiasm and passion which has built it! If you like comfort, good service and dining out then why wait? - go and see your local friendly travel agent NOW!! (And im not being paid for this advice!)	
